# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batch-control-isa88
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] In the manufacturing batch production process, the machines are in chronological order directly related to the manufacturing process.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] The batch production method is also used so any temporary changes or modifications can be made to the product if necessary during the manufacturing process.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] For example, if a product needed a sudden change in material or details changed, it can be done in between batches.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] As opposed to assembly production or mass production where such changes cannot be easily made.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] The time between batches is called cycle time.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] Each batch may be assigned a lot number.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] Because batch production involves small batches, it is good for quality control.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] For example, if there is a mistake in the process, it can be fixed without as much loss compared to mass production.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] This can also save money by taking less risk for newer plans and products etc.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] As a result, this allows batch manufacturing to be changed or modified depending on company needs.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] In certain cases, batch production may require less expensive equipment, thus reducing the capital cost required to set up this type of system.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] There can be downtime between individual batches.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] Or if the product is constantly changing or being modified throughout the process, this also can cost downtime.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] Other disadvantages are that smaller batches need more planning, scheduling and control over the process and collecting data.
[src:batch-control-isa88/batch-production] Because of these factors, items made using batch production may have higher unit cost and take more time compared to continuous production.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA is one of the foremost professional organizations in the world for setting standards and educating industry professionals in automation.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Instrumentation and automation are some of the key technologies involved in nearly all industrialized manufacturing.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Modern industrial manufacturing is a complex interaction of numerous systems.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Instrumentation provides regulation for these complex systems using many different measurement and control devices.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Automation provides the programmable devices that permit greater flexibility in the operation of these complex manufacturing systems.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA is well known for its standards program, which surrounds topics in instrumentation, control systems, operational technology (OT) cybersecurity, and more.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The International Society of Automation is a non-profit member-driven organization, which is built on a backbone of volunteers.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Volunteers, working together with the ISA's full-time staff, are key to the ongoing mission and success of the organization.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA has a strong leadership development program that develops volunteer leaders as they get involved with the organization's many different facets.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA has several different ways that volunteers get involved from the geographic section, training, events, and standards roots of the organization.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA members are typically assigned an ISA Section (local chapter) which is related to their geographic location.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA Standards Committees are open to broad participation from all interested stakeholders regardless of geographic location or membership status.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA was officially established as the Instrument Society of America on 28 April 1945, in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The society grew out of the desire of 18 local instrument societies to form a national organization.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] It was the brainchild of Richard Rimbach of the Instruments Publishing Company.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Rimbach is recognized as the founder of ISA.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Industrial instruments, which became widely used during World War II, continued to play an ever-greater role in the expansion of technology after the war.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Individuals like Rimbach and others involved in industry saw a need for the sharing of information about instruments on a national basis, as well as for standards and uniformity.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The Instrument Society of America addressed that need.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Sperry, chairman of Panelit Corporation, became ISA's first president in 1946.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] In that same year, the Society held its first conference and exhibit in Pittsburgh.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The first standard, RP 5.1 Instrument Flow Plan Symbols, followed in 1949, and the first journal was published in 1954.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] In the years following, ISA continued to expand its products and services, increasing the size and scope of the ISA conference and exhibition, offering professional development and training, and even producing films about measurement and control.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Membership grew from 900 in 1946 to 6,900 in 1953, and as of 2025, ISA members number approximately 17,000 from over 100 countries.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] In 1980, ISA moved its headquarters to Research Triangle Park (RTP), North Carolina, and a training center was established in nearby Raleigh.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] In 2022, the headquarters and training center were consolidated in a new building in RTP, where the society's day-to-day activities are managed by a professional staff.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Recognizing the fact that ISA's technical scope had grown beyond instruments and that its reach went beyond "America," in the fall of 2000 the ISA Council of Society Delegates approved a legal name change to ISA—The Instrumentation, Systems, and Automation Society.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] In 2008, the Council voted to rename the society to the International Society of Automation to reflect its global nature and membership base.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Today, ISA's corporate branding strategy focuses exclusively on the letters, though ISA's official, legal name is the International Society of Automation.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA membership is organized into particular grades: Life, Fellow, Senior Member, Member, and Student Member.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Professional members pay dues of $154 per year, and student dues are $15 annually.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The benefits of ISA membership include, among other things, affiliation with an ISA section (see below), discounts on ISA's products, events and services, and access to technical documents and knowledge through the ISA content portal, Pub Hub.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Local ISA chapters are known as ISA Sections.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Sections are commonly organized around a specific geographic area, e.g.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Seattle Section, Connecticut Valley Section, Greater Oklahoma Section, France Section etc.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] There are 103 chartered sections in 33 countries in North America, South America, Europe, Asia, Africa, and the Middle East.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Many sections sponsor training courses, conduct periodic trade shows, and act as a resource to the local industrial community.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Reflecting their primacy in ISA's early days, sections retain pre-eminent governance authority, as ISA's legislative body, the Council of Society Delegates, is composed of section representatives (delegates) who hold voting power equal to the size of their membership.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA also has nearly 200 student sections, in locations all over the world, principally where the economy has a substantial manufacturing component, and instrumentation and industrial automation are vital academic programs.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Some student sections have found it difficult to remain active, as it is necessary to continually replace graduates with newer students, and membership is consequently very fluid.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Sections are located within districts, of which there are 14, and which comprise large geographic areas of the world.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Districts 1,2,3,5,6,7,8,9, and 11 are in the US (although District 7 also includes Mexico and Central America, and District 3 includes Puerto Rico).
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] District 4 is South America (including the Trinidad Section).
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] District 12 is Europe and the Middle East, and District 14 is the Asia-Pacific sphere.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA formerly had geographic subdivisions known as "regions", which were part of the short lived "ISA International" (1988–1996).
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] At varying intervals following the disestablishment of ISA International, the European Region became District 12, the India Region became District 14, and the South America Region became District 4 [1].
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA standards play a major role in the work of instrumentation and automation professionals.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Many ISA standards have been recognized by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) as approved American National Standards.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA standards are developed using a consensus-based model employing volunteer standards committees of automation professionals from across industries.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The ANSI standards development model is used with standards committees having the characteristics of Openness, Lack of Dominance, Balance, Consensus and a Right of Appeal.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] All ISA standards processes are overseen by the ISA Standards & Practices Board.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] As of 2025, there were more than 3500 participating individuals on ISA standards committees, from over 40 countries.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA standards cover a wide range of concepts of importance to instrumentation and automation professionals.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] An example of one significant ISA standard is the ANSI/ISA-50.02 *Fieldbus Standard for Use in Industrial Control Systems*, which is a product of the ISA-50 Signal Compatibility of Electrical Instruments committee.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA100.11a is for testing and certification of wireless products and systems.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] This standard was approved by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as a publicly available specification, or PAS in September 2011.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA95 is an international standard for developing an automated interface between enterprise and control systems.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] As of 2025, the Society has over 135 published standards, recommended practices, and technical reports.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The International Society of Automation also produces the ISA-62443 standards as part of the information security standards.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The security of private industries and governmental installations are often dependent on the reliable functioning of an Industrial control system.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] This is a highly debated subject that has considerable importance for the security of the critical infrastructure of any country.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] For example: International Society of Automation security standards are mentioned on the United States Computer Emergency Response Team website.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The ISA has formed the ISA Security Compliance Institute to promote and designate cyber-secure products and practices for industrial automation suppliers and operational sites.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA hosts two major international conferences per year: the OT Cybersecurity Summit, typically held in late spring, and the Automation Summit and Expo, held in the fall.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] In 2025, the OT Cybersecurity Summit will be held in Brussels, Belgium, and the Automation Summit and Expo will be held in Lake Buena Vista, Florida.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA Sections will often host their own local trade shows, conferences, member events, and/or sponsored training in their individual geographic areas.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The quarterly publication *ISA Transactions*, published by Elsevier, is a refereed journal of scholarly material, for which the intended audience is research and development personnel from academy and industry in the field of process instrumentation, systems, and automation.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA publishes and distributes books which offer thorough coverage of the world of automation.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The ISA publishes its standards, recommended practices and technical reports in a variety of formats.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] These include printed hardcopy, downloadable PDF, web-based viewable, and network licenses.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA training products include classroom-based training, mobile training courses, in-plant training, online courses, and printed course materials.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The ISA also provides in-house training for a number of large corporations.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The ISA has an online, searchable collection of technical content available to its members.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Pub Hub hosts hundreds of essential resources, including ISA standards, best practices, technical reports, InTech magazine archives, webinars, and e-books.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] ISA manages two certification programs, **Certified Automation Professional** (**CAP**), and Certified Control Systems Technician (CCST).
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Each of these is designed to be an objective, third-party assessment and confirmation of an individual's professional abilities and technical skills.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] Each certification is granted based on a combination of formal education/training, professional experience, and performance on a written examination.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The CCST program was established in the early 1990s and because of an obvious industry need, rapidly gained credibility.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] There are now approximately 4,000 ISA certified technicians worldwide.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The CAP program, launched in 2004, is still in the process of becoming established within the industrial community and gaining recognition.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] As of 2012, there are over 500 certified CAPs worldwide.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The ISA used to have a third certification program called Certified Industrial Maintenance Mechanic (CIMM) which was established in 2004.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] In 2010, the CIMM program was transferred to the Society for Maintenance and Reliability Professionals.
[src:batch-control-isa88/international-society-of-automation] The SMRP renamed the CIMM certification to the Certified Maintenance and Reliability Technician (CMRT).
[src:batch-control-isa88/isa-88] S88 provides a consistent set of standards and terminology for batch control and defines the physical model, procedures, and recipes.
[src:batch-control-isa88/isa-88] The standard sought to address the following problems: lack of a universal model for batch control, difficulty in communicating user requirement, integration among batch automation suppliers, and difficulty in batch-control configuration.
[src:batch-control-isa88/isa-88] The *physical model* begins with the *enterprise*, which may contain a *site*, which may contain *areas*, which may contain *process cells*, which must contain a *unit*, which may contain *equipment modules*, which may contain *control modules*.
[src:batch-control-isa88/isa-88] Some of these levels may be excluded, but not the Unit.
[src:batch-control-isa88/isa-88] The *procedural control model* consists of *recipe procedures*, which consist of an ordered set of *unit procedures*, which consist of an ordered set of *operations*, which consist of an ordered set of *phases.* Some of these levels may be excluded.
[src:batch-control-isa88/isa-88] Recipes can have the following types: general, site, master, control.
[src:batch-control-isa88/isa-88] The contents of the recipe include: header, formula, equipment requirements, procedure, and other information required to make the recipe.
[src:batch-control-isa88/isa-88] Like in Packml, the Machine and Unit States described by this standard are implemented in other standards.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] MES creates the "as-built" record, capturing the data, processes and outcomes of the manufacturing process.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] This can be especially important in regulated industries, such as food and beverage or pharmaceutical, where documentation and proof of processes, events and actions may be required.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] As of 2025, the manufacturing execution systems are shifting from rigid, monolithic on-premise software to modular, cloud-connected platforms.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] "Manufacturing execution systems [help] create flawless manufacturing processes and provide real-time feedback of requirement changes", and provide information at a single source.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] A wide variety of systems arose using collected data for a dedicated purpose.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Further development of these systems during the 1990s introduced overlap in functionality.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Then the Manufacturing Enterprise Solutions Association International (MESA) introduced some structure by defining 11 functions that set the scope of MES.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] In 2000, the ANSI/ISA-95 standard merged this model with the Purdue Reference Model (PRM).
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] A functional hierarchy was defined in which MES were situated at Level 3 between ERP at Level 4 and process control at Levels 0, 1, 2.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] With the publication of the third part of the standard in 2005, activities in Level 3 were divided over four main operations: production, quality, logistics and maintenance.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Between 2005 and 2013, additional or revised parts of the ANSI/ISA-95 standard defined the architecture of an MES into more detail, covering how to internally distribute functionality and what information to exchange internally as well as externally.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Over the years, international standards and models have refined the scope of such systems in terms of activities.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] MES integrates with ISA-95 (previous Purdue Reference Model, “95”) with multiple relationships.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] The collection of systems acting on the ISA-95 Level 3 can be called manufacturing operations management systems (MOMS).
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Apart from an MES, there are typically laboratory information management system (LIMS), warehouse management system (WMS) and computerized maintenance management system (CMMS).
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Examples of systems acting on ISA-95 Level 4 are product lifecycle management (PLM), enterprise resource planning (ERP), customer relationship management (CRM), human resource management (HRM), and process development execution system (PDES).
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] In many cases, middleware enterprise application integration (EAI) systems are being used to exchange transaction messages between MES and Level 4 systems.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] A common data definition, B2MML, has been defined within the ISA-95 standard to link MES systems to these Level 4 systems.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems acting on ISA-95 Level 2 are supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA), programmable logic controllers (PLC), distributed control systems (DCS) and building automation systems (BAS).
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Most MES systems include connectivity as part of their product offering.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Direct communication of plant floor equipment data is established by connecting to the PLC.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Often, plant floor data is first collected and diagnosed for real-time control in a DCS or SCADA system.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] In this case, the MES systems connect to these Level 2 systems for exchanging plant floor data.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] The industry standard for plant floor connectivity has evolved from OLE for Process Control (OPC) to OPC Unified Architecture (OPC-UA).
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Unlike its predecessor, OPC-UA is platform-independent, allowing it to run on Linux and embedded devices while offering robust security models.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] In modern Industry 4.0 architectures, MES connectivity often extends beyond the traditional hierarchy.
[src:batch-control-isa88/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems increasingly utilize IIoT protocols like MQTT (often with Sparkplug B) to transmit lightweight data to cloud-based analytics platforms, creating a hybrid architecture where OPC-UA handles complex machine data and MQTT handles rapid telemetry.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In IPC, control theory provides the theoretical framework to understand system dynamics, predict outcomes and design control strategies to ensure predetermined objectives, utilizing concepts like feedback loops, stability analysis and controller design.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] On the other hand, the physical apparatus of IPC, based on automation technologies, consists of several components.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Firstly, a network of sensors continuously measure various process variables (such as temperature, pressure, etc.) and product quality variables.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] This creates a continuous closed-loop cycle of measurement, comparison, control action, and re-evaluation which guarantees that the process remains within established parameters.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The HMI (Human-Machine Interface) acts as the "control panel" for the IPC system where small number of human operators can monitor the process and make informed decisions regarding adjustments.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] IPCs can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel (controlled environment tank for mixing, separating, reacting, or storing materials in industrial processes.) to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control feedback loops.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] IPC provides several critical benefits to manufacturing companies.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] By maintaining a tight control over key process variables, it helps reduce energy use, minimize waste and shorten downtime for peak efficiency and reduced costs.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] It ensures consistent and improved product quality with little variability, which satisfies the customers and strengthens the company's reputation.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] It improves safety by detecting and alerting human operators about potential issues early, thus preventing accidents, equipment failures, process disruptions and costly downtime.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Analyzing trends and behaviors in the vast amounts of data collected real-time helps engineers identify areas of improvement, refine control strategies and continuously enhance production efficiency using a data-driven approach.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] IPC is used across a wide range of industries where precise control is important.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The applications can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel, to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control loops.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In automotive manufacturing, IPC ensures consistent quality by meticulously controlling processes like welding and painting.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Mining operations are optimized with IPC monitoring ore crushing and adjusting conveyor belt speeds for maximum output.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Dredging benefits from precise control of suction pressure, dredging depth and sediment discharge rate by IPC, ensuring efficient and sustainable practices.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Pulp and paper production leverages IPC to regulate chemical processes (e.g., pH and bleach concentration) and automate paper machine operations to control paper sheet moisture content and drying temperature for consistent quality.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In chemical plants, it ensures the safe and efficient production of chemicals by controlling temperature, pressure and reaction rates.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Oil refineries use it to smoothly convert crude oil into gasoline and other petroleum products.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In power plants, it helps maintain stable operating conditions necessary for a continuous electricity supply.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In food and beverage production, it helps ensure consistent texture, safety and quality.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Pharmaceutical companies relies on it to produce life-saving drugs safely and effectively.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The development of large industrial process control systems has been instrumental in enabling the design of large high volume and complex processes, which could not be otherwise economically or safely operated.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Early process control breakthroughs came most frequently in the form of water control devices.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Ktesibios of Alexandria is credited for inventing float valves to regulate water level of water clocks in the 3rd century BC.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In the 1st century AD, Heron of Alexandria invented a water valve similar to the fill valve used in modern toilets.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Later process controls inventions involved basic physics principles.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel invented a bimetallic thermostat for controlling the temperature in a furnace.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In 1681, Denis Papin discovered the pressure inside a vessel could be regulated by placing weights on top of the vessel lid.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In 1745, Edmund Lee created the fantail to improve windmill efficiency; a fantail was a smaller windmill placed 90° of the larger fans to keep the face of the windmill pointed directly into the oncoming wind.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] With the dawn of the Industrial Revolution in the 1760s, process controls inventions were aimed to replace human operators with mechanized processes.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In 1784, Oliver Evans created a water-powered flourmill which operated using buckets and screw conveyors.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Henry Ford applied the same theory in 1910 when the assembly line was created to decrease human intervention in the automobile production process.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] For continuously variable process control it was not until 1922 that a formal control law for what we now call PID control or three-term control was first developed using theoretical analysis, by Russian American engineer Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Minorsky was researching and designing automatic ship steering for the US Navy and based his analysis on observations of a helmsman.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] He noted the helmsman steered the ship based not only on the current course error, but also on past error, as well as the current rate of change; this was then given a mathematical treatment by Minorsky.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] His goal was stability, not general control, which simplified the problem significantly.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] While proportional control provided stability against small disturbances, it was insufficient for dealing with a steady disturbance, notably a stiff gale (due to steady-state error), which required adding the integral term.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Finally, the derivative term was added to improve stability and control.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] However this required a large manpower resource to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Effectively this was the centralization of all the localized panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] These could be distributed around the plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The distributed control system (DCS) was born.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels in a large process using processor and computer-based control.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] To determine the fundamental model for any process, the inputs and outputs of the system are defined differently than for other chemical processes.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The balance equations are defined by the control inputs and outputs rather than the material inputs.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The control model is a set of equations used to predict the behavior of a system and can help determine what the response to change will be.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The state variable (x) is a measurable variable that is a good indicator of the state of the system, such as temperature (energy balance), volume (mass balance) or concentration (component balance).
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Input variable (u) is a specified variable that commonly include flow rates.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The entering and exiting flows are both considered control inputs.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The control input can be classified as a manipulated, disturbance, or unmonitored variable.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Parameters (p) are usually a physical limitation and something that is fixed for the system, such as the vessel volume or the viscosity of the material.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Output (y) is the metric used to determine the behavior of the system.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The control output can be classified as measured, unmeasured, or unmonitored.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Processes can be characterized as batch, continuous, or hybrid.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Batch applications require that specific quantities of raw materials be combined in specific ways for particular duration to produce an intermediate or end result.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] One example is the production of adhesives and glues, which normally require the mixing of raw materials in a heated vessel for a period of time to form a quantity of end product.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Other important examples are the production of food, beverages and medicine.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Batch processes are generally used to produce a relatively low to intermediate quantity of product per year (a few pounds to millions of pounds).
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] A continuous physical system is represented through variables that are smooth and uninterrupted in time.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The control of the water temperature in a heating jacket, for example, is an example of continuous process control.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Some important continuous processes are the production of fuels, chemicals and plastics.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Continuous processes in manufacturing are used to produce very large quantities of product per year (millions to billions of pounds).
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Such controls use feedback such as in the PID controller A PID Controller includes proportional, integrating, and derivative controller functions.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Applications having elements of batch and continuous process control are often called hybrid applications.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The fundamental building block of any industrial control system is the control loop, which controls just one process variable.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] An example is shown in the accompanying diagram, where the flow rate in a pipe is controlled by a PID controller, assisted by what is effectively a cascaded loop in the form of a valve servo-controller to ensure correct valve positioning.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Some large systems may have several hundreds or thousands of control loops.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] In complex processes the loops are interactive, so that the operation of one loop may affect the operation of another.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The system diagram for representing control loops is a Piping and instrumentation diagram.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Commonly used control systems include programmable logic controller (PLC), Distributed Control System (DCS) or SCADA.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] If a control valve were used to hold level in a tank, the level controller would compare the equivalent reading of a level sensor to the level setpoint and determine whether more or less valve opening was necessary to keep the level constant.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] A cascaded flow controller could then calculate the change in the valve position.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The economic nature of many products manufactured in batch and continuous processes require highly efficient operation due to thin margins.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The competing factor in process control is that products must meet certain specifications in order to be satisfactory.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] These specifications can come in two forms: a minimum and maximum for a property of the material or product, or a range within which the property must be.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] All loops are susceptible to disturbances and therefore a buffer must be used on process set points to ensure disturbances do not cause the material or product to go out of specifications.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] This buffer comes at an economic cost (i.e. additional processing, maintaining elevated or depressed process conditions, etc.).
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Process efficiency can be enhanced by reducing the margins necessary to ensure product specifications are met.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] This can be done by improving the control of the process to minimize the effect of disturbances on the process.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] The efficiency is improved in a two step method of narrowing the variance and shifting the target.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Margins can be narrowed through various process upgrades (i.e. equipment upgrades, enhanced control methods, etc.).
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Once margins are narrowed, an economic analysis can be done on the process to determine how the set point target is to be shifted.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Less conservative process set points lead to increased economic efficiency.
[src:batch-control-isa88/process-control] Effective process control strategies increase the competitive advantage of manufacturers who employ them.
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] It can be used to program processes that can be split into steps.
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] Steps in an SFC diagram can be active or inactive.
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] Actions are only executed for active steps.
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] Steps are activated when all steps above it are active and the connecting transition is superable (i.e. its associated condition is true).
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] When a transition is passed, all steps above are deactivated at once and **after** all steps below are activated at once.
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] Actions associated with steps can be of several types, the most relevant ones being Continuous (N), Set (S), and Reset (R).
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] Apart from the obvious meaning of Set and Reset, an N action ensures that its target variable is set to 1 as long as the step is active.
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] An SFC rule states that if two steps have an N action on the same target, the variable must never be reset to 0.
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] It is also possible to insert LD (Ladder Diagram) actions inside an SFC program (and this is the standard way, for instance, to work on integer variables).
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] SFC is an inherently parallel programming language in that multiple control flows — Program Organization Units (POUs) in the standard's parlance — can be active at once.
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] Non-standard extensions to the language include macroactions: i.e. actions inside a program unit that influence the state of another program unit.
[src:batch-control-isa88/sequential-function-chart] The most relevant such macroaction is "forcing", in which a POU can decide the active steps of another POU.
